    "input": "What should happen before context compaction if exact tool outputs are still only in the chat?",
    "output": "Before the system performs context compaction, you should **copy the exact tool outputs (including the full JSON responses and any intermediate evidence such as screenshots, charts, or logs) into persistent long\u2011term memory**.  \nTypical steps:\n\n| Step | Action | What gets stored |\n|------|--------|------------------|\n| 1 | Call the relevant tool (e.g., `sandbox_execute`, `file_analyze`, `get_portfolio_summary`). | Raw JSON, text, image base64, or CSV | \n| 2 | Immediately after the tool finishes, use **`memory_add`** (or another appropriate memory\u2011storage tool) to store the raw response. | The same content that appears in the chat, *verbatim* (no edits, no summarization). |\n| 3 | Tag the memory with a clear context (e.g., \u201ctool_output_<timestamp>\u201d / \u201cdecision_log_<timestamp>\u201d). | Helps you locate the record later. |\n| 4 | Verify that the memory entry can be retrieved with **`memory_search`** or **`memory_load`** before compaction completes. | Ensures the data survived the transition. |\n\n**Why?**  \nContext compaction strips away conversational history to keep the prompt size manageable. If you rely only on the chat text, any raw tool output that was not explicitly saved will be lost. By persisting it first, you guarantee that downstream skills or future conversations can still access exact evidence, decisions, or intermediate logs.",
